Rational decision-making

01:03:24.000 --> 01:03:32.000
And we are moving on to the third topic of the technique of making rational decisions.

01:03:32.000 --> 01:03:37.000
Within the framework of one video course, it is difficult to disassemble all the techniques.

01:03:37.000 --> 01:03:41.000
We will focus on three of them.

01:03:41.000 --> 01:03:49.000
This is the method of equal exchange, the tree of decisions and the cause-and-effect analysis.

01:03:49.000 --> 01:04:03.000
Those who have made decisions in their life know well that tasks with a single goal are extremely rare.

01:04:03.000 --> 01:04:06.000
Usually, there are several goals.

01:04:06.000 --> 01:04:23.000
And in order to make a decision on several goals, the most rational and, at the same time, the most difficult option for solving the problem is to establish a compromise.

01:04:23.000 --> 01:04:35.000
And the more compromises you have to look for, the more difficult the situation, the more options there are for solving this problem.

01:04:35.000 --> 01:04:46.000
And the more goals the person making the decision pursues, the more preferences he has.

01:04:46.000 --> 01:05:01.000
Peter Drucker, a well-known guru in the field of management, believes that the best solution lies between necessary and erroneous compromises.

01:05:01.000 --> 01:05:09.000
A good leader is experienced enough to understand the difference between them.

01:05:10.000 --> 01:05:29.000
The method that is offered for your consideration and which allows you to find a compromise solution to complex tasks with several options of choice was proposed by John Hammond with the authors.

01:05:29.000 --> 01:05:41.000
And it was called the method of equal exchange, which is essentially a barter deal.

01:05:41.000 --> 01:05:45.000
To exchange one option for another.

01:05:45.000 --> 01:06:02.000
We cannot claim that the application of the method of equal exchange will help you make a difficult solution simple.

01:06:03.000 --> 01:06:14.000
There will still be a difficult choice between what is desirable to achieve and what will have to be sacrificed.

01:06:16.000 --> 01:06:29.000
But the main advantage of the method of equal exchange is that it makes you use a rational, weighted approach to evaluating each compromise.

01:06:29.000 --> 01:06:35.000
And, in fact, it allows you to make the right decision.

01:06:40.000 --> 01:06:48.000
The method of equal exchange is quite difficult to reproduce in a video course.

01:06:48.000 --> 01:06:55.000
It is better to work it out with a pencil in hand and in front of a sheet of paper.

01:06:55.000 --> 01:07:10.000
The manual says that you need to first develop several alternative solutions to the problem, to draw up a so-called table of consequences.

01:07:10.000 --> 01:07:12.000
For example, this is all well disassembled.

01:07:12.000 --> 01:07:27.000
And then, by the method of exception, reduce the number of possible alternative solutions and already between the remaining ones, find a compromise solution.

01:07:27.000 --> 01:07:45.000
The next method, which is widely used in the theory of decision-making, is the tree of solutions.

01:07:45.000 --> 01:07:55.000
The main principle of its construction is the following three points.

01:07:56.000 --> 01:08:00.000
First, you need to formulate a problem.

01:08:00.000 --> 01:08:05.000
This problem is written in the very top corner of the sheet.

01:08:05.000 --> 01:08:15.000
And from this starting point, so-called point, two or more branches go further.

01:08:15.000 --> 01:08:22.000
Usually, there are two branches, because most often at the first stage we answer the question of whether to do it or not.

01:08:22.000 --> 01:08:27.000
To take or not to take, to give or not to give, for example, a loan, and so on.

01:08:27.000 --> 01:08:35.000
And, in fact, these branches denote possible solutions to the problem.

01:08:35.000 --> 01:08:38.000
What direction will these branches take?

01:08:38.000 --> 01:08:42.000
In fact, it does not play a big role.

01:08:42.000 --> 01:08:47.000
There are options when the branches go down from the top point.

01:08:47.000 --> 01:08:55.000
There are solutions when the branches go to the right from the starting point.

01:08:55.000 --> 01:08:58.000
In fact, it does not change.

01:08:58.000 --> 01:09:04.000
But at subsequent levels there are subordinate elements.

01:09:04.000 --> 01:09:05.000
There are three of them.

01:09:05.000 --> 01:09:10.000
These are the solution, the event or state, and the consequences.

01:09:10.000 --> 01:09:15.000
Each of them is denoted by a conditional sign.

01:09:15.000 --> 01:09:23.000
For solutions, this is a circle, for events and states, a square, and for consequences, a triangle.

01:09:25.000 --> 01:09:34.000
From these initial solutions, the following solutions, states or consequences can be branched off.

01:09:34.000 --> 01:09:39.000
And thus a branched tree is built.

01:09:39.000 --> 01:09:49.000
And so it continues until the level when the person making the decision, in general,

01:09:49.000 --> 01:09:56.000
branched off to the last level of consequences or preliminary results.

01:09:59.000 --> 01:10:04.000
The following is important when building a branched tree.

01:10:04.000 --> 01:10:05.000
The following is important.

01:10:05.000 --> 01:10:11.000
At each level, there should be only elements of one type.

01:10:11.000 --> 01:10:14.000
Elements of only one type.

01:10:14.000 --> 01:10:20.000
That is, either only a solution, or only a state, or only consequences.

01:10:22.000 --> 01:10:30.000
The most common practice of making a decision, building a branched tree,

01:10:30.000 --> 01:10:33.000
is a three-layer model.

01:10:33.000 --> 01:10:38.000
The first layer with possible solutions follows the initial question,

01:10:38.000 --> 01:10:41.000
one of which can be chosen.

01:10:41.000 --> 01:10:51.000
Then the second layer of events is introduced, which can occur after this decision has been made.

01:10:51.000 --> 01:10:57.000
And the third layer already contains consequences in each relevant case.

01:10:58.000 --> 01:11:07.000
A branched tree allows to clearly imagine possible solutions along with their consequences

01:11:07.000 --> 01:11:14.000
and to get an idea of the probability of certain consequences.

