01:30:06.000 --> 01:30:17.000
In order to make a decision, you need to develop certain criteria.

01:30:17.000 --> 01:30:20.000
We talked about efficiency criteria.

01:30:20.000 --> 01:30:26.000
Let's look at the term criteria in a slightly different way.

01:30:26.000 --> 01:30:30.000
According to the term criteria, in the theory of decision-making,

01:30:30.000 --> 01:30:35.000
criteria denote a significant, understandable person making a decision,

01:30:35.000 --> 01:30:40.000
the characteristics, results of the operation.

01:30:40.000 --> 01:30:47.000
And there are many alternatives in the field of criteria definition.

01:30:47.000 --> 01:30:51.000
For different alternatives, which is very important,

01:30:51.000 --> 01:30:55.000
a person's criteria can take on different meanings,

01:30:55.000 --> 01:31:04.000
which reflect the consciousness of the person who makes a decision

01:31:04.000 --> 01:31:13.000
and express the degree of his preference for certain alternatives.

01:31:13.000 --> 01:31:22.000
In theory, there is a rule for decision-making.

01:31:22.000 --> 01:31:27.000
If one alternative is more preferable than the other,

01:31:27.000 --> 01:31:38.000
then this more preferable alternative should have a more preferable rating.

01:31:38.000 --> 01:31:45.000
That is, if we choose an alternative with a better rating,

01:31:45.000 --> 01:31:51.000
then it is believed that we choose the best alternative.

01:31:55.000 --> 01:32:01.000
As one of the criteria, when making a decision,

01:32:01.000 --> 01:32:07.000
the so-called rating of usefulness is applied,

01:32:07.000 --> 01:32:12.000
which refers to direct methods.

01:32:12.000 --> 01:32:20.000
It is based on the assumption that the attitude of the person making the decision

01:32:20.000 --> 01:32:25.000
can be represented by the function of usefulness.

01:32:25.000 --> 01:32:35.000
And it can be expressed by the formula that is presented on the slide.

01:32:35.000 --> 01:32:38.000
It is read as follows.

01:32:38.000 --> 01:32:45.000
Alternative A is no less preferable than alternative B.

01:32:45.000 --> 01:32:58.000
Therefore, the function of usefulness should be no less important than that of alternative B.

01:32:58.000 --> 01:33:05.000
Thus, it is only necessary to find an alternative that is most useful,

01:33:05.000 --> 01:33:20.000
and it will be the best for making a decision.

01:33:23.000 --> 01:33:25.000
From the perspective of mathematics,

01:33:25.000 --> 01:33:34.000
there can be several best alternatives with the highest ratings of usefulness,

01:33:34.000 --> 01:33:39.000
since the maximum of the function of usefulness can be achieved

01:33:39.000 --> 01:33:44.000
by several elements of a multitude of definitions.

01:33:44.000 --> 01:33:48.000
In this case, we repeat once again,

01:33:48.000 --> 01:33:58.000
interpretations will help the manager to choose the best solution from the best with the help of preferences.

01:33:58.000 --> 01:34:08.000
When making a decision based on the criteria,

01:34:08.000 --> 01:34:14.000
the so-called Okama principle is very often used,

01:34:14.000 --> 01:34:17.000
or the razor blade.

01:34:17.000 --> 01:34:23.000
This principle states that a razor blade does not multiply an entity without necessity.

01:34:24.000 --> 01:34:29.000
And if we translate this into a simple language,

01:34:29.000 --> 01:34:40.000
it essentially means that if the same phenomenon can be explained by several different circumstances,

01:34:40.000 --> 01:34:46.000
and one of the circumstances is much simpler than the others,

01:34:46.000 --> 01:34:51.000
then the preference should be given to a simpler explanation.

01:34:56.000 --> 01:35:02.000
To make it clear what the coefficient of the assessment of usefulness is,

01:35:02.000 --> 01:35:08.000
let's take an example from the work of the marketing department.

01:35:09.000 --> 01:35:17.000
The criteria for the usefulness of marketing information are assessed as a ratio of the amount of useful,

01:35:17.000 --> 01:35:25.000
that is, the information they need, to the total amount of information coming from the source.

01:35:25.000 --> 01:35:34.000
For example, if a fax comes to the marketing department with a currency exchange rate of 10 foreign currencies,

01:35:34.000 --> 01:35:37.000
and the department uses only one position,

01:35:37.000 --> 01:35:44.000
then the usefulness of the incoming information in this case will be equal to 1 tenth.

01:35:44.000 --> 01:35:51.000
And then the criteria for usefulness are established, that is, its critical value.

01:35:51.000 --> 01:35:59.000
In this case, we can consider this source of information as useful,

01:35:59.000 --> 01:36:04.000
because the lower value of the criteria is set as 5 hundredths.

01:36:07.000 --> 01:36:08.000
Another example.

01:36:08.000 --> 01:36:19.000
We all know that our computers are constantly subjected to the destructive effect of various viruses,

01:36:19.000 --> 01:36:24.000
and have long been accustomed to installing various antivirus programs.

01:36:25.000 --> 01:36:41.000
To this day, we understand that an antivirus program should be able to recognize and protect our computer from all known viruses.

01:36:41.000 --> 01:36:55.000
The function of the usefulness of a computer program in this case is determined by the ratio of the number of viruses caught to all existing ones.

01:36:55.000 --> 01:37:01.000
However, the development of science and technology, including information technology,

01:37:01.000 --> 01:37:11.000
suggests that such an expression of the criteria for usefulness and safety no longer corresponds to reality.

01:37:12.000 --> 01:37:22.000
At present, it is already proposed to assess the usefulness of an antivirus program

01:37:22.000 --> 01:37:31.000
by the ability of the antivirus program to detect unknown viruses.

01:37:31.000 --> 01:37:39.000
That is, it must recognize what is not embedded in the database.

01:37:39.000 --> 01:37:42.000
As we can see, the criteria are changing.

01:37:42.000 --> 01:37:55.000
It should be noted that when choosing a criteria, there are a number of restrictions that vary and depend on both the situation and the specific leaders.

01:37:55.000 --> 01:37:57.000
They are listed on your slide.

01:37:57.000 --> 01:38:05.000
This is the inadequacy of resources, that is, the lack of the necessary resources.

01:38:05.000 --> 01:38:09.000
These are personnel restrictions, financial restrictions.

01:38:09.000 --> 01:38:12.000
I think this is understandable and does not require special comment.

01:38:12.000 --> 01:38:15.000
The restrictions of scientific and technical progress.

01:38:15.000 --> 01:38:23.000
That is, science, so to speak, does not yet offer solutions in this matter.

01:38:23.000 --> 01:38:28.000
These are market restrictions, including the actions of competitors.

01:38:28.000 --> 01:38:38.000
These are legal and moral ethical restrictions, which very often do not allow to make one or another decision.

01:38:38.000 --> 01:38:43.000
And the restriction of authority when choosing a criterion.

01:38:43.000 --> 01:38:54.000
That is, not everyone who makes a decision has all the authority.

01:38:54.000 --> 01:39:05.000
In addition to these listed restrictions, there are also criteria that are called killers.

01:39:05.000 --> 01:39:07.000
This is a term that has developed.

01:39:07.000 --> 01:39:20.000
And killers are called those criteria that must be taken into account, otherwise the decision will simply not make sense.

01:39:20.000 --> 01:39:24.000
This can be explained by an elementary example.

01:39:24.000 --> 01:39:35.000
If a person has no driving license, he cannot look for a job as a private driver, so to speak, or just a driver.

01:39:35.000 --> 01:39:52.000
If a person, so to speak, has an allergy to flowers, then he will not go to rest where the grass is just blooming now, and so on.

01:39:52.000 --> 01:40:08.000
And the second point by which the criterion can be called a killer is all those circumstances that a decision-maker would like to avoid.

01:40:08.000 --> 01:40:18.000
Here we again face a subjective point, but this is a very important concept.

01:40:19.000 --> 01:40:22.000
It can be illustrated by the example.

01:40:22.000 --> 01:40:39.000
If a person is an introvert, it is difficult for him to work in communication with people, then he will probably not look for a job in the service sector, a job with clients,

01:40:39.000 --> 01:40:45.000
and most likely he will find a job in the production sector or in the back office.

01:40:45.000 --> 01:40:54.000
Well, the time has come to choose an alternative.

01:40:54.000 --> 01:40:56.000
How is it done?

01:40:56.000 --> 01:41:03.000
First of all, all possible options for solving the problem must be identified.

01:41:04.000 --> 01:41:18.000
Then you need to limit the number of options for comparison with several alternatives using the above criteria, preferences, judgments, compromises, and so on.

01:41:18.000 --> 01:41:30.000
Next, it is necessary to evaluate all the effective alternatives and compare them with each other for the next choice of the best of them.

01:41:31.000 --> 01:41:46.000
In this case, the assessment assumes the determination of both a positive and a negative effect of introducing an alternative solution.

01:41:46.000 --> 01:41:50.000
Well, the final point is to choose an alternative.

01:41:50.000 --> 01:42:15.000
To choose the right alternative, it is necessary, as a rule, to take into account the previous experience, although, as we noted, you can not always rely entirely and completely on the past experience.

01:42:15.000 --> 01:42:21.000
The second is to conduct an experiment.

01:42:21.000 --> 01:42:26.000
And the third is to conduct a study and analysis.

01:42:26.000 --> 01:42:44.000
The past experience becomes a useful tool in making decisions if it is a thorough analysis, and not a blind follow-up to what has already been done.

01:42:44.000 --> 01:42:49.000
That is, a blind copy of what has already been done once.

01:42:50.000 --> 01:42:53.000
Conducting an experiment.

01:42:53.000 --> 01:43:03.000
Perhaps, for some alternatives, conducting an experiment is difficult or impossible.

01:43:03.000 --> 01:43:09.000
But if there is such an opportunity, then the experiment must be conducted.

01:43:10.000 --> 01:43:13.000
What is meant by the word experiment?

01:43:13.000 --> 01:43:19.000
This is an experiment to test alternatives in artificially created conditions.

01:43:22.000 --> 01:43:35.000
Let's suppose that the developers of the passive safety systems of the car offer an alternative option of a safety pillow.

01:43:36.000 --> 01:43:53.000
Artificial conditions can be created to test how the pillow will behave in certain artificially created extreme conditions, how it will contribute to the safety of the passenger, and so on.

01:43:54.000 --> 01:44:14.000
As for the study and analysis, the solution of the problem should be considered based on the search for the connections between its alternatives and the restrictions that are considered regarding the set goals.

01:44:14.000 --> 01:44:21.000
It is also useful to decompose the problem into separate components.

01:44:21.000 --> 01:44:26.000
This is the essence of the analysis.

01:44:26.000 --> 01:44:38.000
To study each of these elements separately, so that after making a synthesis, you can come to a justified solution.

01:44:44.000 --> 01:44:48.000
